column20: The plastic surgery residency at Scott & White is 1 of 4 programs participating in an ACGME-approved educational innovation. The residency is a competency-based as opposed to a time based training program. Under the competency-based model, training is a minimum of 5 instead of 6 years. The American Board of Plastic Surgery has approved this educational innovation, and graduates of the residency are eligible for fellowships and to enter the board certification process.

column20: The CDPH PMRP trains physicians for careers in California public health agencies. Residents are placed across California, depending on their preferences. CDPH prefers applicants who have completed a primary care residency, but welcomes all applicants. Although a clinical experience is part of this program, the emphasis is on a broad exposure to population health. We aim to improve the health of all Californians, with a focus on vulnerable populations and those impacted by health disparities.
